The paper deals with the computation and learning of Nash equilibria in large-population games, which is a topic that falls under game theory (cs.GT). The use of efficient algorithms and machine learning techniques suggests that the paper may also be relevant to artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also involves the analysis of algorithms and the use of data structures, which are topics that fall under computer science (cs.DS). Finally, the paper deals with the representation of games and the centralization of player influence, which may be relevant to social and information networks (cs.SI).
